{"meta":{"authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:21 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:21 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">The verb <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span> “to need” or “to have to” is used either as the main verb of a sentence or as the modal verb. It is also used as an auxiliary in the allocentric future constructions (xxlink 23.3.2 allocentric future).<\/p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Like many other languages, Tibetan has certain defective modal verbs. This is the case with verb <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span>, insofar as there are certain restrictions about how it can be combined with auxiliaries. As a main verb it means “to need” or “to want.” <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span> occurs only with the following auxiliaries, and its various tenses (future, present, past) have to be deduced from the context.<\/p> <table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"> <tbody> <tr> <td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Egophoric<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"69\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་ཡོད་<\/span> “I need”<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"77\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་མེད་<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"> <\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"69\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span> “I want”<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"77\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative:<\/p> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མི་དགོས་<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Testimonial<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"69\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་འདུག་<\/span> “you, he need(s)”<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"77\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་མི་འདུག་<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"69\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་རེད་<\/span> “you, he need(s)”<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"77\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་མ་རེད་<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <\/tbody> <\/table> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The suffix <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་<\/span> may be inserted between the modal and the auxiliary: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་<\/span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་<\/span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདུག་<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་<\/span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རེད་<\/span>, but it is usually dropped in conversation. As shown above, the verb may occur alone without auxiliary <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span> or <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མི་དགོས་<\/span> and may then be best translated as “I (do not) want,” while with the auxiliary it may be translated as “need.” This negation is not pronounced <em>mi <\/em>as expected but rather is <em>mu<\/em>.<\/p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The subject of <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མི་དགོས་<\/span> used as a main verb must be in the dative and the object in the absolutive. In constructing a sentence, the beneficiary comes first and the patient second.<\/p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ངར་ཁ་བཏགས་དགོས་ཡོད།<\/span> “I need offering-scarves.”<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ངར་ཇ་མི་དགོས།<\/span> “I don’t want any tea.”<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོང་ལ་ཆབ་དགོས་གནང་གི་འདུག<\/span> “He needs\/wants water (H).”<\/li> <\/ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">As a modal verb <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span> means “to have to,” “to need,” or even “must.” In Tibetan, unlike European languages, modal verbs such <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཆོག་<\/span>, and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཐུབ་<\/span> do not have an epistemic function and may not indicate probability or certainty (as in “he may be there, he must be there, etc.”). For the auxiliaries devoted to this function, see the discussion of epistemic mood here in the Reference Grammar (xxlink 11.3.1 epistemic); see also the discussions of the modal epistemic verb <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྲིད་<\/span> (xxlink 11.3.6 modal verbs).<\/p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The modal verb <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span> goes with the following auxiliaries:<\/p> <table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"> <tbody> <tr> <td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Future:<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་ཀྱི་རེད་<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Present:<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Egophoric<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་<\/span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"> <\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Testimonial<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་<\/span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདུག་<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"> <\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་<\/span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རེད་<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Past (perfective):<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Egophoric<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བྱུང་<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"> <\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Testimonial<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བྱུང་སོང་<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"93\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"> <\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"91\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"87\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བྱུང་པ་རེད་<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <\/tbody> <\/table> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Conjugations of <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span> are formed in the same way as predicative adjectives such as <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགའ་པོ་<\/span> “like\/be fond of.” The forms *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་སོང་<\/span>, *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བཞག<\/span> and *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་པ་རེད་<\/span> are usually not acceptable.<\/p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The case of the subject depends on the main verb.<\/p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྒྱང་ཤེལ་བསྣམས་དགོས་རེད།<\/span> “(We) have to take binoculars.”<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ང་ཁ་བཏགས་ཉོ་དགོས་ཡོད།<\/span> “I have to buy offering-scarves.”<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ངས་དངུལ་སྤྲད་དགོས་བྱུང་།<\/span> “I had to pay (for it).”<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོང་རི་ལིའི་ནང་ལ་ཕེབས་དགོས་བྱུང་སོང་།<\/span> “He had to take the train.”<\/li> <\/ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Egophoric<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་ཡོད་<\/span> “I need”<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་མེད་<\/span><\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"> <\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span> “I want”<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative:<\/p> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མི་དགོས་<\/span><\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Testimonial<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་འདུག་<\/span> “you, he need(s)”<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་མི་འདུག་<\/span><\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་རེད་<\/span> “you, he need(s)”<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Negative: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་མ་རེད་<\/span><\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Future:<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་ཀྱི་རེད་<\/span><\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Present:<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Egophoric<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་<\/span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཡོད་<\/span><\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"> <\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Testimonial<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་<\/span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདུག་<\/span><\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"> <\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་<\/span>(<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཀྱི་<\/span>)<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རེད་<\/span><\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Past (perfective):<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Egophoric<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བྱུང་<\/span><\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"> <\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Testimonial<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བྱུང་སོང་<\/span><\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"> <\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\">Assertive<\/p>  <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དགོས་བྱུང་པ་རེད་<\/span><\/p> ","title":""}]}